      <h3>Dangerous Wild Life</h3>
      <h1>Venomous snakes</h1>
      <img src="/snek.jpg" alt="snakes" class="smaller-image">
      <p>While Italy offers a wealth of natural beauty and captivating experiences, it's essential to be aware of potential hazards, including the presence of some dangerous snake species. Although encounters with venomous snakes are relatively rare, certain regions, particularly in the southern parts of the country, are home to species like the European adder (Vipera berus) and the nose-horned viper (Vipera ammodytes). These snakes are generally shy and tend to avoid humans, but it's prudent to exercise caution when exploring rural or wooded areas, especially during warmer months when they might be more active.</p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>Staying on well-trodden paths, wearing appropriate footwear, and being attentive to your surroundings can go a long way in minimizing the risk of snake encounters and ensuring a safe and enjoyable journey through Italy's diverse landscapes...</p>
    </div>
    <h1>Brown Bears</h1>
        <img src="/bear.jpg" alt="Brown bear" class="smaller-image">
      <p>Although direct interactions with these bears are quite rare, certain regions, particularly in the northern parts of the country such as the Apennine Mountains, are home to the Italian brown bear (Ursus arctos marsicanus). These bears are naturally reclusive and tend to avoid human contact. However, when venturing into remote or wooded areas, especially in their habitats, it's wise to exercise caution. Staying on established paths, making noise to alert bears of your presence, and carrying bear bells can help reduce the chances of unexpected encounters. </p>
