  <h3>Natural Disasters</h3>
  <h1>Floods</h1>
      <img src="/Flood.jpg" alt="flood" class="smaller-image">
      <p>It's essential to be mindful of potential natural hazards, including the occurrence of floods. Although widespread flooding is relatively uncommon, certain regions, particularly those prone to heavy rainfall or situated near rivers and coastlines, can experience periodic flooding. It's advisable to exercise caution when traveling through flood-prone areas, especially during the rainy seasons or when weather conditions are unstable.</p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>Staying informed about local weather forecasts and potential flood alerts, avoiding low-lying areas, and refraining from crossing flooded roads or rivers can significantly mitigate the risk of encountering hazardous situations. By staying prepared, adhering to safety recommendations, and respecting the power of nature, you can ensure a secure and pleasant journey through Italy's diverse landscapes.</p>
    </div>
    <h1>Earthquakes</h1>
        <img src="/earthquakeItaly.jpg" alt="earthquake" class="smaller-image">
      <p> Italy is situated in a seismically active area, and certain regions, particularly along the Apennine fault system and around the Adriatic Sea, are more susceptible to earthquakes. Although major seismic events are infrequent, it's prudent to be prepared and informed. When visiting earthquake-prone areas, consider familiarizing yourself with local emergency procedures and evacuation routes. Booking accommodations that adhere to seismic safety standards can provide added peace of mind. In the unlikely event of an earthquake, remember to "Drop, Cover, and Hold On" during the shaking, and once it subsides, follow the guidance of local authorities and be cautious of potential aftershocks.<a href="https://team-100-agile.github.io/earthquake/">Click here to go through an example scenario</a></p>
