        <h3>Etiquette</h3>
        <h1>Greetings</h1>
      <img src="/italygreetings.jpg" alt="Greeting" class="smaller-image">
      <p>In Italy, greetings and personal space are intricately woven into the fabric of social interactions. Handshakes are a common form of greeting, reflecting warmth and respect. When close friends and family meet, they might exchange kisses on the cheek, a gesture that signifies familiarity and camaraderie. However, it's important to note that personal space is highly respected in Italian culture. Conversations are often held at a comfortable distance, allowing individuals to engage without encroaching on each other's personal spheres. </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>This delicate balance of physical closeness and spatial respect mirrors the Italian commitment to creating meaningful connections while acknowledging the need for individual boundaries. By embracing these customs, visitors can seamlessly integrate into the social tapestry of Italy and convey their respect for its cultural nuances.</p>
    </div>
    <h1>Religious Sites</h1>
        <img src="/italyreligioussites.jpg" alt="Religious Sites" class="smaller-image">
      <p>Respect for religious sites in Italy is a fundamental aspect of cultural sensitivity and appreciation. When entering churches or other religious spaces, it's essential to adhere to a code of conduct that reflects the sanctity of these places. Dressing appropriately is a sign of reverence; wearing clothing that covers shoulders, cleavage, and knees is expected. This demonstrates an understanding of the spiritual significance these sites hold. Additionally, maintaining a quiet and respectful demeanor acknowledges the sacred atmosphere and allows others to engage in their spiritual practices undisturbed. Moreover, it's important to be mindful of the rules regarding photography. </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p> Some areas within religious sites might prohibit photography to preserve the solemnity of the space. By following these guidelines, visitors can participate in a meaningful exchange with Italy's religious heritage while demonstrating their respect for its cultural and spiritual essence.</p>
